## Concurrency

### Goroutine hygiene

- **Never start a goroutine without knowing when it will stop.**
- Always pass a `context.Context` for cancellation.
- Use `sync.WaitGroup` or `errgroup` to wait for goroutines.

```go
// ✅ Good — goroutines are bounded, errors collected
func processItems(ctx context.Context, items []Item) error {
    g, ctx := errgroup.WithContext(ctx)
    sem := make(chan struct{}, 10) // limit concurrency to 10

    for _, item := range items {
        item := item // capture loop variable (pre-Go 1.22)
        g.Go(func() error {
            sem <- struct{}{}
            defer func() { <-sem }()
            return process(ctx, item)
        })
    }
    return g.Wait()
}
```

### Channel patterns

```go
// Done channel for signaling
done := make(chan struct{})
defer close(done)

// Buffered channel for work queues
jobs := make(chan Job, 100)

// Select with timeout
select {
case result := <-resultCh:
    return result, nil
case <-time.After(5 * time.Second):
    return nil, ErrTimeout
case <-ctx.Done():
    return nil, ctx.Err()
}
```

### Mutex usage

```go
type Cache struct {
    mu    sync.RWMutex
    items map[string]Item
}

func (c *Cache) Get(key string) (Item, bool) {
    c.mu.RLock()
    defer c.mu.RUnlock()
    item, ok := c.items[key]
    return item, ok
}

func (c *Cache) Set(key string, item Item) {
    c.mu.Lock()
    defer c.mu.Unlock()
    c.items[key] = item
}
```

